  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 18.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Wheresoever it taketh him",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "καταλάβη",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); literally, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "it seizeth hold of him.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "  This is the Greek word from which comes our \"catalepsy,\" the active form of \"epilepsy.\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "It teareth him",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ῤήσσει",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). This is doubtless the literal meaning. But there is much evidence to show that it means here \"it striketh or throweth him down.\" This is the reudering of the Peshito Syriac, and of the Vulgate. The same interpretation is also given by Hesychius as one of the meanings of the word. St. Luke (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 9:39",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") describes the symptoms thus: \"A spirit taketh him, and he suddenly crieth out, and it teareth him (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "σπαράσσει αὐτὸν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") that he foameth (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "μετὰ ἀφροῦ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and it hardly departeth from him, bruising him sorely.\" This it will be remembered is the record of one who was himself a physician. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "He grindeth his teeth, and pineth away",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ξηραίνεται",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), as though the springs of his life were dried up. The father of the boy is here minutely describing the symptoms when the fit was upon him. He seems here to express the stiffness and rigidity of the body in the approaches of the malady. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And I spake to thy disciples that they should cast it out; and they were not able",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". They had tried and failed. This failure is attributed by our Lord (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 17:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") to their want of faith; or rather to their \"little faith (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "διὰ τὴν ὀλιγοπιστίαν ὑμῶν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ").\" Mark 9:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Vincent's Word Studies",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "It taketh him (καταλάβῃ)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Lit., seizeth hold of him. Our word catalepsy is derived from this.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Teareth (ῥήσσει)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Rev., dasheth down, with rendeth in margin. The verb is a form of ῥήγνυμι, to break. The form ῥήσσω is used in classical Greek of dancers beating the ground, and of beating drums. Later, in the form ῥάσσειν, a term of fighters: to fell, or knock down, which is the sense adopted by Rev.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Gnasheth with his teeth",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Rev., grindeth. This and the pining away are peculiar to Mark. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]